{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636016","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636016"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:22:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:22:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17557"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17557","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17557"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.29,0.17,0.23,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10247"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76192"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10247","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10247"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17557"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61696"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6703"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23955"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23970"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76192","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76192"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe deep venous drainage of the brain follows a systematic pattern, with various structures draining into larger collecting vessels.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the normal venous drainage pathway of the internal cerebral veins?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Drain directly into the superior sagittal sinus","Join with other tributaries to form the great cerebral vein","Drain via tributary vessels into the transverse sinus","Connect with other vessels to form the inferior sagittal sinus","Empty directly into the cavernous sinus"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe internal cerebral veins \u003Cstrong\u003Ejoin with other tributaries to form the great cerebral vein\u003C/strong\u003E. This is the primary drainage pathway for deep structures of the brain including the basal ganglia, thalamus and choroid plexus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrain directly into the superior sagittal sinus\u003C/strong\u003E - The superior sagittal sinus primarily receives blood from the superficial cortical veins\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDrain via tributary vessels into the transverse sinus\u003C/strong\u003E - The transverse sinus receives blood from the veins draining the cerebellum and inferior surface of the cortex \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EConnect with other vessels to form the inferior sagittal sinus\u003C/strong\u003E - The inferior sagittal sinus runs alongthe inferior edge of the falx cerebri, draining the medial aspect of the cerebral hemispheres. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmpty directly into the cavernous sinus\u003C/strong\u003E - The cavernous sinus receives blood from ophthalmic veins and the superficial middle cerebral vein,\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe great cerebral vein, also known as the vein of Galen, subsequently joins with the inferior sagittal sinus to form the straight sinus, which then drains into the transverse sinus.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The internal cerebral veins drain deep structures of the brain including the basal ganglia and thalamus.","The great cerebral vein (of Galen) is formed by the union of multiple veins including the internal cerebral veins.","The great cerebral vein joins with the inferior sagittal sinus to form the straight sinus."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61696"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17557"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61696","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61696"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-02T11:42:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-02T11:43:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10247"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76192"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emed